barter, bargain, price, property’ + <i>mann</i> ‘man’.","Jewish: adopted probably for a like-sounding or like-meaning name in some other European language; see for example   Kaufman  .","History: This name was brought independently to North America from England by numerous different bearers from the 17th century onward. John Chapmen (sic) was one of the free planters who assented to the ‘Fundamental Agreement’ of the New Haven Colony on June 4, 1639."],"variants":[{"name":"Chatman","meanings":["English: altered form of   Chapman  ."]},{"name":"Kaufman","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Hyman, Meyer, Chaim, Emanuel, Moshe, Eytan, Herschel, Zvi, Ari, Aron.","Americanized form of German   Kaufmann  , and a variant of the same Jewish surname.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): from the personal name <i>Kaufman</i> meaning ‘merchant’. Compare   Koyfman   2."]},{"name":"Chipman","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>chipman</i> (Old English <i>cȳp(e)mann</i>), a side form of <i>chapman</i>, <i>chepman</i> ‘merchant, trader’; see   Chapman  , with which this name was interchangeable."]},{"name":"Copeman","meanings":["English (Norfolk and Suffolk): patronymic from the early Middle English personal name <i>Cop(e)man</i>, an Anglicized form of Old Scandinavian <i>Kaupmaðr</i>. It is a transferred use of Old Scandinavian <i>kaupmaðr</i> (Old Danish <i>køpman</i>) ‘merchant’, cognate with Old English <i>cēapmann</i> (see   Chapman  ), but there is no evidence for the occupational term in Middle English.","Americanized form of North German   Koopmann   or Dutch   Koopman  ."]}]},{"name":"Anne","type":"FIRST","meanings":["A name corrpted from Hannah, q.v. It is also found several times in a male name. From Ann, Anne, we have as nicknames Nan and Nancy"],"variants":[{"name":"Nancy","meanings":["Of uncertain origin. From the 18th century it is clearly used as a pet form of   Ann   (  see  Nan  ), but it may originally have been a similar formation deriving from the common medieval given name   Annis  , a vernacular form of   Agnes .  Nowadays it is an independent name, and was especially popular in America in the 1930s, 40s, and 50s."]},{"name":"Nan","meanings":["Originally a pet form of   Ann   (for the initial <i>N-</i>,  compare  Ned  ). It is now also widely used as a short form of   Nancy ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":29,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Anne Chapman was born in 1426, in London, England. She married Thomas Belwood in 1441, in London, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"1426–":"1426–Surnud","1424–1444":"1424–1444","1440–1503":"1440–1503","1426–Female":"1426–Surnud","1426":"1426","1503":"1503","1424":"1424","1455":"1455","1444":"1444","before 1440":"enne 1440","1441":"1441","1440":"1440","about 1460":"umbes 1460","Belton, Lincolnshire, England":"Belton, Lincolnshire, England","London, England":"London, England"},"fi":{"1426–":"1426–Kuollut","1424–1444":"1424–1444","1440–1503":"1440–1503","1426–Female":"1426–Kuollut","1426":"1426","1503":"1503","1424":"1424","1455":"1455","1444":"1444","before 1440":"ennen vuotta 1440","1441":"1441","1440":"1440","about 1460":"noin 1460","Belton, Lincolnshire, England":"Belton, Lincolnshire, England","London, England":"London, England"},"fr":{"1426–":"1426–Décédée","1424–1444":"1424–1444","1440–1503":"1440–1503","1426–Female":"1426–Décédée","1426":"1426","1503":"1503","1424":"1424","1455":"1455","1444":"1444","before 1440":"avant 1440","1441":"1441","1440":